  "response": "When you bite the inside of your lip, the area becomes swollen or inflamed due to the injury. This swelling can create a raised or more prominent surface in your mouth, making it more likely for your teeth to graze or bite the same spot again as you chew, speak, or move your mouth. Additionally, your body's natural response to the injury (such as increased blood flow and sensitivity) can make the area more noticeable to your tongue and teeth, further increasing the chances of re-biting it.\n\nAnother factor is that biting your lip can temporarily alter the way you chew or move your mouth, sometimes unconsciously, as your body tries to avoid the painful area. This altered movement can ironically lead to accidentally biting the same spot again. The cycle of re-injury can continue until the swelling subsides and the area heals completely.",
